    "instruction": "Analyze trace.csv for any traces that involve Mysql02. Do the following (use full series to compute thresholds, then filter to the incident window 2021-03-23 02:30:00 to 2021-03-23 03:00:00 UTC+8):\n1) Find all trace rows where either the cmdb_id equals 'Mysql02' OR the trace_name string contains 'Mysql02' (case-sensitive substring match). If none, return the top 20 trace rows within the incident window where trace_name contains 'Mysql' (to capture calls to/from MySQL services).\n2) For each distinct trace_name found in step 1, compute the global P95 over the full available series (no time filtering).\n3) For each such trace_name, compute compact aggregates limited to the incident window: points_in_window, breach_count (value > global P95), first_breach_timestamp (earliest in window where value > P95 or null), max_value_in_window, p95_threshold, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / p95_threshold.\n4) Return only trace_name rows that have breach_count > 0, limited to top 20 sorted by severity_ratio descending. Also return the total number of distinct trace_name scanned and the number that had breaches. Keep output tabular and bounded (max 20 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The trace analysis returned no records for Mysql02 (neither cmdb_id == 'Mysql02' nor trace_name containing 'Mysql' within the incident window), so trace data cannot corroborate or localize the Mysql02 metric anomalies. From metric analysis we have strong candidates: two Mysql02 fsync-related KPIs breached at 2021-03-23 02:34:00 UTC+8 (p95==0 -> new/rare event), but they are single-point breaches (breach_count=1) and thus could be symptomatic rather than causal. Other anomalies (MG01 disk read/Bps and OSLinux disk/CPU KPIs on Tomcat/MG/apache hosts) show breaches at or before 02:32–02:36. To decide the root cause (single failure) we must find which faulty KPI first appeared in time and whether that fault is a sustained fault (consecutive anomalies) rather than an isolated spike. Since traces did not include Mysql02, the next logical actions are: 1) identify the earliest metric breach across all component-KPIs (to find the first-occurrence fault candidate), and 2) inspect log metrics for those components around the earliest breach times to seek corroborating evidence. Traces are unavailable for Mysql02, so logs and metric timing must be used for localization.",
