    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and limiting to the allowed possible root-cause components list [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02], compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full series (no time filtering). Then filter metric rows to the incident window 2021-03-23 02:30:00 to 2021-03-23 03:00:00 UTC+8. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) that has any point > global P95 in the window, compute: points_in_window, breach_count, first_breach_timestamp (earliest timestamp in window where value > P95), max_value_in_window, p95_threshold, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / p95_threshold. Return a compact table of up to 20 rows sorted by first_breach_timestamp ascending (earliest breaches first). Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs scanned and the number of pairs that had breaches. Keep outputs bounded (<=20 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Metric-level analysis scanned 1,712 component-KPI pairs and found 544 pairs with values exceeding their global P95 during the incident window. Many breaches begin right at 02:30, indicating the degradation started at or before that minute. Top early/high-severity candidates include Tomcat02 (CPU-3), apache01 (disk write/WTps), IG01 (network KB/s), several disk I/O metrics on MG/Tomcat, and MySQL anomalies: Mysql02 showed fsync-related metrics with an infinite severity (p95==0, max==1) at 02:34, while Mysql01 shows CPU and disk write anomalies beginning 02:30–02:31. Trace data did not contain rows for Mysql02, so we could not corroborate Mysql02 via traces. To localize the root cause among the many early breaches, we need trace evidence for the top candidate hosts (Tomcat02, apache01, IG01, Mysql01, Mysql02, Tomcat01, MG01/MG02, Tomcat04) to see whether trace latencies or failures point to a downstream faulty component and to determine ordering in the call graph. No final root cause has been confirmed yet.",
